text: To the people criticising me tonight about the protests in Russia, I have one question, do you think there would have been protests yesterday if mobilisation wasn't declared yesterday? If not, why not? And if not, how do you expect Ukrainians to react to that?
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

text: Without boring you all by repeating myself, I fully support the protesters, I think they are acting with incredible courage & I send them my solidarity. But I'm much more interested in how Ukrainians feel right now than what the mood is like in Moscow. I won't apologise for that.

text: As Russia's military commissariats begin rounding up reservists for the front, we're seeing fairly clear -- if inevitably anecdotal -- evidence that the call-up is falling hardest on the communities already hardest hit by the war, particularly ethnic minorities.\n\n/1
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

text: Racism and classism are absolutely part of this process. Wars are almost always fought by the disenfranchised, marginalized and the poor on behalf of the powerful -- and Russia is no exception in that regard.\n\n/8
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

text:
But there is also a more mundane -- and, for Putin, a more problematic -- reason behind this: Bureaucratic inertia.

Tasked with mobilizing as many men as possible as quickly as possible, the military is going for the easiest targets.

/9
